# 13) One-Page Narrative

## Backfill Shifts: Why this can become the primary operating mode

Most hourly businesses do not have a scheduling problem in the abstract. They have an operations problem: building next week’s schedule, getting it to the team, and surviving when the real world breaks it.

That is why Backfill Shifts matters.

Traditional schedulers ask managers to live inside a scheduling product. Backfill Shifts does the opposite. It makes scheduling the input to a more important job: keeping shifts covered. The system drafts the week, summarizes the exceptions by text, lets the manager approve or review, then handles callouts and open shifts using the same communication layer.

This changes the center of gravity.

For customers with an existing scheduler, Backfill can still connect to it. But for businesses using spreadsheets, whiteboards, or ad hoc texting, Backfill Shifts can become the operating mode itself. If the manager can publish next week by replying APPROVE, and if callouts route automatically without the manager opening a dashboard unless something unusual happens, then many customers will not feel the need to adopt a heavyweight scheduler at all.

That is the wedge.

Backfill Shifts is not trying to replace payroll, time clocks, HR, or every compliance rule under the sun. It is deliberately narrow. It focuses on the core loop that matters most to an hourly-work manager:

1. get next week ready,
2. notify the team,
3. handle changes fast,
4. fill gaps before service breaks.

The product strategy follows directly from that loop.

First, Backfill Shifts must have a durable data model. If the customer never connects Deputy or Homebase, Backfill’s roster, shift history, lifecycle states, and amendments become the operational source of truth.

Second, recurring schedule reuse becomes retention. The product must make “copy last week and tweak” or “review the AI draft and approve” easier than rebuilding schedules from scratch.

Third, text-first control becomes the differentiator. Existing products already support schedule creation, copying, publishing, and automation. Backfill’s advantage is not feature breadth; it is workflow compression. Managers do not need another heavy admin system if the AI handles the schedule and the coverage in one flow.

That is why Backfill Shifts should be built as a primary-capable operating mode from day one.

Not because every customer will use it that way.

Because some of the best customers will.

And if it works, Backfill stops being just a backfill tool.

It becomes the lightweight operating system for hourly shift continuity.

# 14) V1 Sprint Plan and Ticket Breakdown

## Read this first: repo-aligned execution order

The detailed sprint plan below was written as if the product were starting from zero. That is not the current repo. The actual execution order for this codebase should be:

1. Extend the current operational ledger rather than replace it.
   Codex owns the migration/API plan that adds schedule containers, schedule versions, shift assignments, and import job state on top of the existing `organizations` / `locations` / `workers` / `shifts` / `cascades` model.

2. Freeze backend contracts before parallel UI work.
   Claude should build against locked JSON examples for schedule summary, weekly grid payloads, import status/action-needed rows, and publish/amend deep links.

3. Treat coverage as an extension of the existing cascade engine.
   We should not build a new `coverage_workflows` engine first and leave `cascades` running beside it. Either evolve `cascades` into the new model or add a thin compatibility layer with a clear migration path.

4. Defer auth and full RBAC.
   There is no manager auth system in the repo today. Backfill Shifts v1 should use the current internal/admin access model plus manager phone identity, then layer true RBAC later if pilot requirements force it.

5. Build in this order:
   a. schema extension + API contracts
   b. roster/import foundation
   c. schedule lifecycle + assignments + weekly grid
   d. publish/amend + employee delivery
   e. inbound callout/open-shift writeback using the existing messaging/cascade stack

